Now inequality (2,1) > (3,1): r2c1 > r3c1.

Row2c1 {1,2,4,6} but 1 already used in column1, so r2c1 ∈ {2,4,6}. Row3c1 {1,2,3,5,6} but 1 not allowed (col1 already has 1 used but could still have another 1? No each column must have each number once, so 1 already used, can't repeat. So r3c1 ∈ {2,3,5,6}. And r2c1 > r3c1.

Now column5 we still need assign.

Row3c5 {5,6}. Row4c5 {3,5,6}. Row5c5 {3,6}. Row6c5 {1,3,5,6}.

But note column5 still missing numbers {1,3,5,6}. Since 4 used, 2 used.

We have r5c5 cannot be 1 (since set {3,6}). So 1 must be either r6c5. Good: only r6c5 includes 1. Therefore r6c5 =1.

Thus column5 now remaining numbers {3,5,6} for rows 3,4,5.

r3c5 {5,6}
r4c5 {3,5,6}
r5c5 {3,6}

Now row6 has now numbers: c3=2, c5=1. Row6 missing {3,4,5,6}. Positions:
